# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rf-amplifiers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A **class-D amplifier**, or **switching amplifier**, is an electronic amplifier in which the amplifying devices (transistors, usually MOSFETs) operate as electronic switches, and not as linear gain devices as in other amplifiers.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] They operate by rapidly switching back and forth between the supply rails, using pulse-width modulation, pulse-density modulation, or related techniques to produce a pulse train output.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A low-pass filter is typically used to attenuate their high-frequency content to provide analog output current and voltage.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Little energy is dissipated in the amplifying transistors because they are always either fully on or fully off, so efficiency can exceed 90%.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Switching amplifier circuits corresponding to what is now termed class-D operation were described in the early 1930s, including an electric amplifying circuit patented by Burnice D.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Pulse-width and pulse-time modulation techniques were further developed later in the 1930s by Alec Reeves for telecommunication signaling and transmission, rather than for power amplification.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The term class-D was proposed in 1959 by P.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Baxandall in the context of transistor oscillators.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] High efficiency is obtained by arranging for the active devices to pass current only when the associated voltage is low.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In Baxandall’s circuit, this was achieved using an inductor to steer current between devices, minimizing the overlap of voltage and current during conduction.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The first commercial product was a kit module called the X-10 released by Sinclair Radionics in 1964.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] However, it had an output power of only 2.5 watts.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The Sinclair X-20 in 1966 produced 20 watts but suffered from the inconsistencies and limitations of the germanium-based bipolar junction transistors available at the time.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] As a result, these early class-D amplifiers were impractical and unsuccessful.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Practical class-D amplifiers were enabled by the development of silicon-based MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor) technology.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In 1978, Sony introduced the TA-N88, the first class-D unit to employ power MOSFETs and a switched-mode power supply.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] There were subsequently rapid developments in MOSFET technology between 1979 and 1985.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The availability of low-cost, fast-switching MOSFETs led to class-D amplifiers becoming successful in the mid-1980s.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In 1983, Mead Killion applied for a patent describing an integrated-circuit class-D amplifier intended for use in hearing aids.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A class-D-amplifier-based integrated circuit was released by Tripath in 1996.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Phase-modulated class-D architectures have also been developed.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In these designs, a high-power switching waveform is generated on the primary side and shared across channels.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Phase displacement is generated during demodulation according to the input signal and produces a pulse-width-modulated output.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A phase-modulated class-D audio amplifier was described in a patent assigned to Peavey Electronics, in which the AC mains are rectified only to drive the primary switching stage, with no secondary-side DC supply rails, and the output is recovered using a low-pass filter.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers work by generating a train of rectangular pulses of fixed amplitude but varying width and separation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This *modulation* represents the amplitude variations of the analog audio input signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In some implementations, the pulses are synchronized with an incoming digital audio signal, removing the necessity to convert the signal to analog.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The output of the modulator is then used to turn the output transistors on and off alternately.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Since the transistors are either fully on or fully off, they dissipate very little power.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A simple low-pass filter consisting of an inductor and a capacitor provides a path for the low frequencies of the audio signal, leaving the high-frequency pulses behind.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The structure of a class-D power stage is comparable to that of a synchronously rectified buck converter, a type of non-isolated switched-mode power supply (SMPS).
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Whereas buck converters usually function as voltage regulators, delivering a constant DC voltage into a variable load, and can only source current, a class-D amplifier delivers a constantly changing voltage into a fixed load.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A switching amplifier may use any type of power supply (e.g., a car battery or an internal SMPS), but the defining characteristic is that the amplification process itself operates by switching.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Some class-D amplifiers use more than two output voltage levels to improve efficiency and reduce component size by switching in smaller voltage steps.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This reduces switching ripple current and allows the use of smaller output inductors.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] One implementation uses flying-capacitor half-bridges to produce three-level waveforms from a single supply rail, or five-level waveforms in bridge-tied-load configurations.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This has been demonstrated in monolithic audio power amplifiers.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] An alternative approach generates multiple output voltage levels using stacked or series-connected switching devices, without flying capacitors, in which voltage stress is shared across devices while the output stage generates multilevel PWM.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The theoretical power efficiency of class-D amplifiers using ideal switches is 100%.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] That is to say, all of the power supplied to it is delivered to the load, and none is turned to heat.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This is because an ideal switch in its *on* state would encounter no resistance and conduct all the current with no voltage drop across it, hence no power would be dissipated as heat.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] And when it is *off*, it would have the full supply voltage across it but no leakage current flowing through it, and again no power would be dissipated.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Real-world power MOSFETs are not ideal switches, but practical efficiencies well over 90% are common for class-D amplifiers.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] By contrast, linear AB-class amplifiers are always operated with both current flowing through and voltage standing across the power devices.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] An ideal class-B amplifier has a theoretical maximum efficiency of 78%.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Class-A amplifiers (purely linear, with the devices always at least partially *on*) have a theoretical maximum efficiency of 50%, and some designs have efficiencies below 20%.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The 2-level waveform is derived using pulse-width modulation (PWM), pulse-density modulation (sometimes referred to as pulse frequency modulation), sliding mode control (more commonly called *self-oscillating modulation*) or discrete-time forms of modulation such as delta-sigma modulation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A simple means of creating the PWM signal is to use a high-speed comparator ("**C**" in the block diagram above) that compares a high-frequency triangular wave with the audio input.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This generates a series of pulses, of which the duty cycle is directly proportional to the instantaneous value of the audio signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The comparator then drives a MOS gate driver, which in turn drives a pair of high-power switching transistors (usually MOSFETs).
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This produces an amplified replica of the comparator's PWM signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The output filter removes the high-frequency switching components of the PWM signal and reconstructs audio information that the speaker can use.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] DSP-based amplifiers that generate a PWM signal directly from a digital audio signal (e.g., SPDIF) either use a counter to time the pulse length or implement a digital equivalent of the triangle-based modulator.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In either case, the time resolution afforded by practical clock frequencies is only a few hundredths of a switching period, which is not enough to ensure low noise.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In effect, the pulse length gets quantized, resulting in quantization distortion.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In both cases, negative feedback is applied inside the digital domain, forming a noise shaper which results in lower noise in the audible frequency range.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Two significant design challenges for MOSFET driver circuits in class-D amplifiers are keeping dead times and linear mode operation as short as possible.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] *Dead time* is the period during a switching transition when both output MOSFETs are driven into cut-off mode and both are *off*.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Failures that allow shoot-through or too much linear mode operation result in excessive losses and sometimes catastrophic failure of the MOSFETs.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] With fixed-frequency PWM modulation, as the (peak) output voltage approaches either of the supply rails, the pulse width can get so narrow as to challenge the ability of the driver circuit and the MOSFET to respond.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] These pulses can be as short as a few nanoseconds and can result in shoot-through and heating due to linear mode operation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Other modulation techniques, such as pulse-density modulation, can achieve higher peak output voltages, as well as greater efficiency compared to fixed-frequency PWM.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers place an additional requirement on their power supply, namely that it be able to sink energy returning from the load.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Reactive (capacitive or inductive) loads store energy during part of a cycle and release some of this energy back later.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Linear amplifiers will dissipate this energy; class-D amplifiers return it to the power supply, which should somehow be able to store it.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] In addition, half-bridge class-D amplifiers transfer energy from one supply rail (e.g., the positive rail) to the other (e.g., the negative) depending on the sign of the output current.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This happens with both resistive and reactive loads.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The supply should either have enough capacitive storage on both rails, or be able to transfer this energy to the other rail.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The active devices in a class-D amplifier need only act as controllable switches and need not have a particularly linear response to the control input.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The actual output of the amplifier is not just dependent on the content of the modulated PWM signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A number of sources may introduce errors.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Any variation in power supply voltage directly amplitude-modulates the output voltage.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Dead time errors make the output impedance non-linear.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The output filter has a strongly load-dependent frequency response.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] An effective way to combat errors, regardless of their source, is negative feedback.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] A feedback loop including the output stage can be made using a simple integrator.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] To include the output filter, a PID controller is used, sometimes with additional integrating terms.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The need to feed the actual output signal back into the modulator makes the direct generation of PWM from a SPDIF source unattractive.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Mitigating the same issues in an amplifier without feedback requires addressing each separately at the source.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Power supply modulation can be partially canceled by measuring the supply voltage to adjust signal gain as part of PWM conversion.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Distortion can be reduced by switching faster.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The output impedance cannot be controlled other than through feedback.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] The major advantage of a class-D amplifier is that it can be much more efficient than a linear amplifier, dissipating less power as heat in the active devices.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] This is especially compelling in compact portable, battery-powered devices.
[src:rf-amplifiers/class-d-amplifier] Also, given that large heat sinks are not required, class-D amplifiers are much lighter weight than class-A, -B, or -AB amplifiers, an important consideration with portable sound reinforcement system equipment and bass amplifiers.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The design of the distributed amplifiers was first formulated by William S.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] In that year Percival proposed a design by which the transconductances of individual vacuum tubes could be added linearly without lumping their element capacitances at the input and output, thus arriving at a circuit that achieved a gain-bandwidth product greater than that of an individual tube.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Percival's design did not gain widespread awareness however, until a publication on the subject was authored by Ginzton, Hewlett, Jasberg, and Noe in 1948.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] It is to this later paper that the term *distributed amplifier* can actually be traced.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Traditionally, DA design architectures were realized using vacuum tube technology.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] More recently, III-V semiconductor technologies, such as GaAs and InP have been used.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] These have superior performance resulting from higher bandgaps (higher electron mobility), higher saturated electron velocity, higher breakdown voltages and higher-resistivity substrates.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The latter contributes much to the availability of higher quality-factor (Q-factor or simply Q) integrated passive devices in the III-V semiconductor technologies.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] To meet the marketplace demands on cost, size, and power consumption of monolithic microwave integrated circuits (MMICs), research continues in the development of mainstream digital bulk-CMOS processes for such purposes.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The continuous scaling of feature sizes in current IC technologies has enabled microwave and mm-wave CMOS circuits to directly benefit from the resulting increased unity-gain frequencies of the scaled technology.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] This device scaling, along with the advanced process control available in today's technologies, has recently made it possible to reach a transition frequency (ft) of 170 GHz and a maximum oscillation frequency (fmax) of 240 GHz in a 90 nm CMOS process.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The operation of the DA can perhaps be most easily understood when explained in terms of the traveling-wave tube amplifier (TWTA).
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The DA consists of a pair of transmission lines with characteristic impedances of Z0 independently connecting the inputs and outputs of several active devices.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] An RF signal is thus supplied to the section of transmission line connected to the input of the first device.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] As the input signal propagates down the input line, the individual devices respond to the forward traveling input step by inducing an amplified complementary forward traveling wave on the output line.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] This assumes the delays of the input and output lines are made equal through selection of propagation constants and lengths of the two lines and as such the output signals from each individual device sum in phase.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Terminating resistors Zg and Zd are placed to minimize destructive reflections.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The transconductive gain of each device is gm and the output impedance seen by each transistor is half the characteristic impedance of the transmission line.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Neglecting losses, the gain demonstrates a linear dependence on the number of devices (stages).
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Unlike the multiplicative nature of a cascade of conventional amplifiers, the DA demonstrates an additive quality.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] It is this synergistic property of the DA architecture that makes it possible for it to provide gain at frequencies beyond that of the unity-gain frequency of the individual stages.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] In practice, the number of stages is limited by the diminishing input signal resulting from attenuation on the input line.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Means of determining the optimal number of stages are discussed below.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Bandwidth is typically limited by impedance mismatches brought about by frequency dependent device parasitics.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The DA architecture introduces delay in order to achieve its broadband gain characteristics.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] This delay is a desired feature in the design of another distributive system called the distributed oscillator.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Delay lines are made of lumped elements of L and C.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The parasitic L and the C from the transistors are used for this and usually some L is added to raise the line impedance.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Because of the Miller effect in the common source amplifier the input and the output transmission line are coupled.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] For example, for voltage inverting and current amplifying the input and the output form a shielded balanced line.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The current is increasing in the output transmission line with every subsequent transistor, and therefore less and less L is added to keep the voltage constant and more and more extra C is added to keep the velocity constant.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] This C can come from parasitics of a second stage.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] These delay lines do not have a flat dispersion near their cut off, so it is important to use the same L-C periodicity in the input and the output.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] If inserting transmission lines, input and output will disperse away from each other.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] For a distributed amplifier the input is fed in series into the amplifiers and parallel out of them.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] To avoid losses in the input, no input signal is allowed to leak through.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] This is avoided by using a balanced input and output also known as push–pull amplifier.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Then all signals which leak through the parasitic capacitances cancel.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The output is combined in a delay line with decreasing impedance.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] For narrow band operation other methods of phase-matching are possible, which avoid feeding the signal through multiple coils and capacitors.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] This may be useful for power-amplifiers.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The single amplifiers can be of any class.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] There may be some synergy between distributed class E/F amplifiers and some phase-matching methods.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Only the fundamental frequency is used in the end, so this is the only frequency, which travels through the delay line version.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Because of the Miller effect a common source transistor acts as a capacitor (non inverting) at high frequencies and has an inverting transconductance at low frequencies.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The channel of the transistor has three dimensions.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] One dimension, the width, is chosen depending on the current needed.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The trouble is for a single transistor parasitic capacitance and gain both scale linearly with the width.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] For the distributed amplifier the capacitance – that is the width – of the single transistor is chosen based on the highest frequency and the width needed for the current is split across all transistors.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Note that those termination resistors are usually not used in CMOS, but the losses due to these are small in typical applications.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] In solid state power amplifiers often multiple discrete transistors are used for power reasons anyway.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] If all transistors are driven in a synchronized fashion a very high gate drive power is needed.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] For frequencies at which small and efficient coils are available distributed amplifiers are more efficient.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Voltage can be amplified by a common gate transistor, which shows no miller effect and no unit gain frequency cut off.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] Adding this yields the cascode configuration.
[src:rf-amplifiers/distributed-amplifier] The common gate configuration is incompatible with CMOS; it adds a resistor, that means loss, and is more suited for broadband than for high efficiency applications.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] The **Doherty amplifier** is a high-efficiency linear radio-frequency power amplifier originally developed for high-power amplitude-modulated broadcasting.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Doherty of Bell Telephone Laboratories in 1936 as a means of maintaining high efficiency over the modulation cycle, particularly in transmitters operating at tens to hundreds of kilowatts, where power consumption and operating cost were significant concerns.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] In the classical Doherty configuration, one amplifier tube (carrier) supplies the required output power under unmodulated carrier conditions, while a second tube (peaking) conducts only during positive modulation peaks.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Through a coupling network, the load impedance presented to the carrier amplifier is dynamically reduced as the peaking amplifier contributes power.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] This allows both tubes to operate at high efficiency throughout the modulation cycle and to share the power required for positive modulation peaks.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] The coupling network functions as a quarter-wave impedance inverter, and the carrier and peaking amplifiers are driven with radio-frequency signals that are ninety degrees out of phase.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Early Western Electric Doherty systems used a modulated driver transmitter, typically 5 kW in 50 kW broadcast installations, with the Doherty amplifier providing the final power stage.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] After its introduction in 1936, the Doherty amplifier progressed from a laboratory demonstration into commercial broadcast equipment.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Western Electric developed and marketed AM broadcast transmitters using the Doherty architecture, documenting their installation and use in contemporary promotional literature.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Later historical reviews indicate that some broadcast stations operating these transmitters reported reductions in operating costs, particularly in electrical power consumption.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] A retrospective article in ''Radio World'' describes broadcaster claims of lower utility expenses and reduced heat dissipation attributed to higher average efficiency, especially under typical program conditions where full modulation peaks occurred infrequently.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] These reports reflect how the Doherty amplifier was perceived by broadcasters in practical service rather than in controlled performance tests.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] The technical influence of the Doherty amplifier extended well beyond its initial broadcast applications.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Doherty applied for the original patent in 1936, and it was issued in 1940 as U.S.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] This patent was cited extensively in later work, including at least 154 subsequent patents.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Subsequent patents explored variations on the original concept while retaining the principle of dynamic load sharing.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] These included alternative circuits and device operating modes.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] A later patent by Weldon described a configuration in which one stage operated as a cathode follower, illustrating refinement of the original architecture rather than its replacement.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] Modern analyses have revisited classical high-efficiency RF power amplifier techniques, such as those of Doherty, and have shown their continued relevance.
[src:rf-amplifiers/doherty-amplifier] A detailed analysis is given in the 2002 literature.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] Load-pull is required when superposition is no longer applicable, which occurs under large-signal operating conditions that make linear approximations unusable.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] The term load-pull derives from classical oscillator characterization whereupon variation of the load impedance pulls the oscillation center frequency away from nominal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] Source-pull is also used for noise characterization, which, although linear, requires multiple impedances to be presented at the source to enable simultaneous solution of an over-determined system that yields the four noise parameters.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] Load-pull is the most common method globally for RF and MW power amplifier (PA) design, transistor characterization, semiconductor process development, and ruggedness analysis.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] With automated load-pull, it is possible to fully optimize and design a final stage for GSM applications in less than a day, thereby providing a dramatic reduction in design cycle-time while assuring the best possible performance trade-off has been achieved.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] While there are in theory no physical limits on the frequency of which load-pull can be performed, most load-pull systems are based on passive distributed networks using either the slab transmission line in its TEM mode or the rectangular waveguide in its TE10 mode.
[src:rf-amplifiers/load-pull] Lumped tuners can be made for HF and VHF frequencies, whereas active load-pull is ideal for on-wafer mm-wave environments, where substantial loss between the tuner and DUT reference-plane limits maximum VSWR.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] A **radio-frequency power amplifier** (**RF power amplifier**) is a type of electronic amplifier that converts a low-power radio-frequency (RF) signal into a higher-power signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Typically, RF power amplifiers are used in the final stage of a radio transmitter, their output driving the antenna.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Design goals often include gain, power output, bandwidth, power efficiency, linearity (low signal compression at rated output), input and output impedance matching, and heat dissipation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The operation of RF amplifier circuits is classified based on the proportion of the cycle of the sinusoidal radio signal the amplifier (transistor or vacuum tube) where current is conducting.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Class-A, class-AB and class-B are considered the linear amplifier classes in which the active device is used as a controlled current source, while class-C is a nonlinear class in which the active device is used as a switch.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The bias at the input of the active device determines the class of the amplifier.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] A common trade-off in power amplifier design is the trade-off between efficiency and linearity.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The previously named classes become more efficient, but less linear, in the order they are listed.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Operating the active device as a switch results in higher efficiency, theoretically up to 100%, but lower linearity.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Among the switch-mode classes are class-D, class-E and class-F.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The class-D amplifier is not often used in RF applications because the finite switching speed of the active devices and possible charge storage in saturation could lead to a large I-V product, which deteriorates efficiency.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Modern RF power amplifiers use solid-state devices, predominantly MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors).
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The earliest MOSFET-based RF amplifiers date back to the mid-1960s.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Bipolar junction transistors were also commonly used in the past, up until they were replaced by power MOSFETs, particularly LDMOS transistors, as the standard technology for RF power amplifiers by the 1990s,BJT are still commonly used for high frequency power amplifiers.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Generally speaking, solid-state power amplifiers (SSPA) contain four main components: input, output, amplification stage and power supply.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] MOSFET transistors and other modern solid-state devices have replaced vacuum tubes in most electronic devices, but tubes are still used in some high-power transmitters (see Valve RF amplifier).
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Although mechanically robust, transistors are electrically fragile – they are easily damaged by excess voltage or current.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Tubes are mechanically fragile but electrically robust – they can handle remarkably high electrical overloads without appreciable damage.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The basic applications of the RF power amplifier include driving to another high-power source, driving a transmitting antenna and exciting microwave cavity resonators.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Among these applications, driving transmitter antennas is most well known.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The transmitter–receivers are used not only for voice and data communication but also for weather sensing (in the form of a radar).
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] RF power amplifiers using LDMOS (laterally diffused MOSFET) are the most widely used power semiconductor devices in wireless telecommunication networks, particularly mobile networks.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] LDMOS-based RF power amplifiers are widely used in digital mobile networks such as 2G, 3G, and 4G and the good cost/performance ratio make them the preferred option for amateur radio.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] Impedance transformations over large bandwidth are difficult to realize, so conventionally, most wideband amplifiers are designed to feed a 50 Ω output load.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] is chosen so that the rated power can be met.
[src:rf-amplifiers/rf-power-amplifier] The loadline method is often used in RF power amplifier design.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A **traveling-wave tube** (**TWT**, pronounced "twit") or **traveling-wave tube amplifier** (**TWTA**, pronounced "tweeta") is a specialized vacuum tube that is used in electronics to amplify radio frequency (RF) signals in the microwave range.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] It was invented by Andrei Haeff around 1933 as a graduate student at Caltech, and its present form was invented by Rudolf Kompfner in 1942–43.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The TWT belongs to a category of "linear beam" tubes, such as the klystron, in which the radio wave is amplified by absorbing power from a beam of electrons as it passes down the tube.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A major advantage of the TWT over some other microwave tubes is its ability to amplify a wide range of frequencies i.e. a large bandwidth.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The bandwidth of the helix TWT can be as high as two octaves, while the cavity versions have bandwidths of 10–20%.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Operating frequencies range from 300 MHz to 50 GHz.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The power gain of the tube is on the order of 40 to 70 decibels, and output power ranges from a few watts to megawatts.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWTs are widely used as the power amplifiers and oscillators in radar systems, communication satellite and spacecraft transmitters, and electronic warfare systems.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The TWT is an elongated vacuum tube with an electron gun (a heated cathode that emits electrons) at one end.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A voltage applied across the cathode and anode accelerates the electrons towards the far end of the tube, and an external magnetic field around the tube focuses the electrons into a beam.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] At the other end of the tube the electrons strike the "collector", which returns them to the circuit.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Wrapped around the inside of the tube, just outside the beam path, is a helix of wire, typically oxygen-free copper.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The RF signal to be amplified is fed into the helix at a point near the emitter end of the tube.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The signal is normally fed into the helix via a waveguide or electromagnetic coil placed at one end, forming a one-way signal path, a directional coupler.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] By controlling the accelerating voltage, the speed of the electrons flowing down the tube is set to be similar to the speed of the RF signal running down the helix.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The signal in the wire causes a magnetic field to be induced in the center of the helix, where the electrons are flowing.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Depending on the phase of the signal, the electrons will either be sped up or slowed down as they pass the windings.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] This causes the electron beam to "bunch up", known technically as "velocity modulation".
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The resulting pattern of electron density in the beam is an analog of the original RF signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Because the beam is passing the helix as it travels, and that signal varies, it causes induction in the helix, amplifying the original signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] By the time it reaches the other end of the tube, this process has had time to deposit considerable energy back into the helix.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A second directional coupler, positioned near the collector, receives an amplified version of the input signal from the far end of the RF circuit.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Attenuators placed along the RF circuit prevent the reflected wave from traveling back to the cathode.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Higher powered helix TWTs usually contain beryllium oxide ceramic as both a helix support rod and in some cases, as an electron collector for the TWT because of its special electrical, mechanical, and thermal properties.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] There are a number of RF amplifier tubes that operate in a similar fashion to the TWT, known collectively as velocity-modulated tubes.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] All of these tubes use the same basic "bunching" of electrons to provide the amplification process, and differ largely in what process causes the velocity modulation to occur.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] In the klystron, the electron beam passes through a hole in a resonant cavity which is connected to the source RF signal.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The signal at the instant the electrons pass through the hole causes them to be accelerated (or decelerated).
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The electrons enter a "drift tube" in which faster electrons overtake the slower ones, creating the bunches, after which the electrons pass through another resonant cavity from which the output power is taken.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Since the velocity sorting process takes time, the drift tube must often be several feet long.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] In comparison, in the TWT the acceleration is caused by the interactions with the helix along the entire length of the tube.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] This allows the TWT to have a very low noise output, a major advantage of the design.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] More usefully, this process is much less sensitive to the physical arrangement of the tube, which allows the TWT to operate over a wider variety of frequencies.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWT's are generally at an advantage when low noise and frequency variability are useful.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Helix TWTs are limited in peak RF power by the current handling (and therefore thickness) of the helix wire.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] As power level increases, the wire can overheat and cause the helix geometry to warp.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Wire thickness can be increased to improve matters, but if the wire is too thick it becomes impossible to obtain the required helix pitch for proper operation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Typically helix TWTs achieve less than 2.5 kW output power.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The **coupled-cavity TWT** overcomes this limit by replacing the helix with a series of coupled cavities arranged axially along the beam.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] This structure provides a helical waveguide, and hence amplification can occur via velocity modulation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Helical waveguides have very nonlinear dispersion and thus are only narrowband (but wider than klystron).
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A coupled-cavity TWT can achieve 60 kW output power.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Operation is similar to that of a klystron, except that coupled-cavity TWTs are designed with attenuation between the slow-wave structure instead of a drift tube.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The slow-wave structure gives the TWT its wide bandwidth.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A free electron laser allows higher frequencies.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A TWT integrated with a regulated power supply and protection circuits is referred to as a traveling-wave-tube amplifier (abbreviated **TWTA** and often pronounced "TWEET-uh").
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] It is used to produce high-power radio frequency signals.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The bandwidth of a broadband TWTA can be as high as one octave, although tuned (narrowband) versions exist; operating frequencies range from 300 MHz to 50 GHz.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A TWTA consists of a traveling-wave tube coupled with its protection circuits (as in klystron) and regulated power supply electronic power conditioner (EPC), which may be supplied and integrated by a different manufacturer.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The main difference between most power supplies and those for vacuum tubes is that efficient vacuum tubes have depressed collectors to recycle kinetic energy of the electrons, so the secondary winding of the power supply needs up to 6 taps of which the helix voltage needs precise regulation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The subsequent addition of a linearizer (as for inductive output tube) can, by complementary compensation, improve the gain compression and other characteristics of the TWTA; this combination is called a linearized TWTA (LTWTA, "EL-tweet-uh").
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Broadband TWTAs generally use a helix TWT and achieve less than 2.5 kW output power.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWTAs using a coupled cavity TWT can achieve 15 kW output power, but at the expense of narrower bandwidth.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The original design and prototype of the TWT was done by Andrei "Andy" Haeff c.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] 1931 while he was working as a doctoral student at the Kellogg Radiation Laboratory at Caltech.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] His original patent, "Device for and Method of Controlling High Frequency Currents", was filed in 1933 and granted in 1936.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The invention of the TWT is often attributed to Rudolf Kompfner in 1942–1943.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] In addition, Nils Lindenblad, working at RCA (Radio Corporation of America) in the USA also filed a patent for a device in May 1940 that was remarkably similar to Kompfner's TWT.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Both of these devices were improvements over Haeff's original design as they both used the then newly invented precision electron gun as the source of the electron beam and they both directed the beam down the center of the helix instead of outside of it.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] These configuration changes resulted in much greater wave amplification than Haeff's design as they relied on the physical principles of velocity modulation and electron bunching.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Kompfner developed his TWT in a British Admiralty radar laboratory during World War II.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] His first sketch of his TWT is dated November 12, 1942, and he built his first TWT in early 1943.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The TWT was later refined by Kompfner, John R.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Note that Kompfner's US patent, granted in 1953, does cite Haeff's previous work.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] By the 1950s, after further development at the Electron Tube Laboratory at Hughes Aircraft Company in Culver City, California, TWTs went into production there, and by the 1960s TWTs were also produced by such companies as the English Electric Valve Company, followed by Ferranti in the 1970s.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] On July 10, 1962, the first communications satellite, Telstar 1, was launched with a 2 W, 4 GHz RCA-designed TWT transponder used for transmitting RF signals to Earth stations.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Syncom 2 was successfully launched into geosynchronous orbit on July 26, 1963, with two 2 W, 1850 MHz Hughes-designed TWT transponders — one active and one spare.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWTAs are commonly used as amplifiers in satellite transponders, where the input signal is very weak and the output needs to be high power.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWTAs used in satellite communications are considered as reliable choices and tend to live beyond their expected lifetime of 15-20 years.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A TWTA whose output drives an antenna is a type of transmitter.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWTA transmitters are used extensively in radar, particularly in airborne fire-control radar systems, and in electronic warfare and self-protection systems.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] In such applications, a control grid is typically introduced between the TWT's electron gun and slow-wave structure to allow pulsed operation.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] The circuit that drives the control grid is usually referred to as a grid modulator.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] TWTAs have found applications in a number of spacecraft, including all five of the space probes that have achieved the escape velocity to leave the Solar System.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] For example, dual redundant 12-watt X-band TWTAs are mounted on the body under the dish of the New Horizons spacecraft, which visited Pluto in 2015, then Kuiper belt object 486958 Arrokoth in 2019 to return data at a distance of 43.4 AU from the Sun.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] Launched in 2021, James Webb Space Telescope makes use of Ka-band TWTs.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] A TWT has sometimes been referred to as a "traveling-wave amplifier tube" (TWAT), although this term was never widely adopted.
[src:rf-amplifiers/travelling-wave-tube] "TWT" has been pronounced by engineers as "twit", and "TWTA" as "tweeta".
